{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539849"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:47:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:47:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16714"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16714"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.01,0,0.02,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66516"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9405"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51969"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1490"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4095"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11116"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43644"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66516"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with a 2 year history of chronic pelvic pain. The pain is dull and constant, worse with movement. She takes no regular medications. She doesn\u0027t feel the pain relates to regular menses. Menses are usually regular and light. She is on the combined oral contraceptive pill. She hasn\u0027t had a cervical screening test as she is under 25 years of age and no abdominal bleeding. She has had chlamydia infections twice previously treated with oral antibiotics. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The abdomen is soft with mild tenderness on deep palpation of the lower abdomen. There is no guarding or rebound or any masses felt. There is no cervical motion tenderness is present on vaginal examination. Transvaginal ultrasound shows no abnormalities. She undergoes diagnostic laparoscopy which reveals adhesions between the anterior surface of the liver and the anterior abdominal wall. There are filmy adhesions between the Fallopian tubes and the side wall and ovaries. Peritoneum otherwise appears normal. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fitz-Hugh-Curtis syndrome","Chronic appendicitis","Constipation","Inflammatory bowel disease","Endometriosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic pelvic pain and laparoscopic findings of perihepatic adhesions. The characteristic \u0027violin string\u0027 adhesions between the liver capsule and anterior abdominal wall, combined with a history of previous chlamydia infections, strongly support a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003EFitz-Hugh-Curtis syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition represents a perihepatitis that occurs as a complication of pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), most commonly caused by \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic appendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with right lower quadrant pain and would show inflammation around the appendix on laparoscopy. The perihepatic adhesions seen in this case would not be explained by appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConstipation\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain the laparoscopic findings of adhesions, and while it can cause chronic abdominal pain, it would typically be associated with changes in bowel habits and respond to laxative therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with additional symptoms such as diarrhoea, weight loss, or blood in stool. Laparoscopy would reveal inflammatory changes in the bowel rather than the characteristic perihepatic adhesions seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometriosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pelvic pain and adhesions, but typically presents with cyclical pain related to menses and would show characteristic dark, powder-burn lesions throughout the pelvis on laparoscopy. The perihepatic adhesions seen here are not typical of endometriosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of Fitz-Hugh-Curtis syndrome involves appropriate antibiotic therapy for PID. While the acute inflammation typically resolves with treatment, the adhesions may persist and cause chronic pain. The presence of these adhesions in a young woman with previous sexually transmitted infections makes this the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fitz-Hugh-Curtis syndrome presents with perihepatic adhesions (\u0027violin string adhesions\u0027) visible on laparoscopy.","This syndrome occurs in up to 30% of patients with pelvic inflammatory disease."],"references":["Sharma JB, Malhotra M, Arora R. Incidential Fitz-Hugh-Curtis syndrome at laparoscopy for benign gynecologic conditions. Int J Gynaecol Obstet. 2002 Dec;79(3):237-40. doi: 10.1016/s0020-7292(02)00231-x. PMID: 12445989.","Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. The Initial Management of Chronic Pelvic Pain: Green-top Guideline No. 41 [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2012 [cited 2024 Nov 30]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/media/muab2gj2/gtg_41.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51969"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16714"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51969"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T18:20:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T18:21:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9405"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66516"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",